00:46:00.430 --> 00:46:05.259
the Carter Administration and then when Reagan
won the White House, he basically was, had

00:46:05.259 --> 00:46:10.770
to figure out, "Hey, do we continue on this
road or not?" And they decided to do it. Again,

00:46:10.770 --> 00:46:14.690
strict conditions were imposed on Chrysler.
Here's the remarkable thing about that. The

00:46:14.690 --> 00:46:21.049
U.S. taxpayers actually made money on that
deal. We made, we as a nation, made about

00:46:21.049 --> 00:46:27.150
$400 million on that Chrysler bailout and
the reason is, is at that time, the government

00:46:27.150 --> 00:46:31.510
got--the government, in that case, did not
provide any direct loans to Chrysler provided

00:46:31.510 --> 00:46:36.210
guarantees of loans made by private banks
and private lenders. But in return for those

00:46:36.210 --> 00:46:42.220
guarantees, the government got warrants to
buy Chrysler stock. When the K car came out,

00:46:42.220 --> 00:46:46.760
Plymouth, Aries, Dodge, Reliant and then the
minivans came out, Chrysler stock went from

00:46:46.760 --> 00:46:53.680
like, two to sixty. Sort of like Google, you
know? In the early days at least. Let's hope

00:46:53.680 --> 00:46:59.569
again. But the government made a lot of money
on those warrants. Actually, one of the most

00:46:59.569 --> 00:47:04.839
outrageous things though, was that Lee Iacocca,
the CEO of Chrysler, thought the government

00:47:04.839 --> 00:47:09.700
was making obscene profits on Chrysler stock,
even though the government had saved the company,

00:47:09.700 --> 00:47:13.400
so he called the Secretary of the Treasury
and said, "You ought to not exercise those

00:47:13.400 --> 00:47:17.670
warrants. You outta just let them lapse."
They got in a shouting match and said some

00:47:17.670 --> 00:47:22.619
words that I can't say on TV, even Google
internal TV, but anyway, we made money on

00:47:22.619 --> 00:47:23.710
that deal.

